observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor ensure strict compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and CSC Memorandum Circular No. 12 s. 2012 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances to avoid accumulation of outstanding cash advances;

(ii) make a formal request for the writing-off of unliquidated cash advances for deceased AOs supported by the necessary documents prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005; and

(iii) instruct the Municipal Accountant to: (a) continue requiring immediate liquidation from present employees with outstanding cash advances by consistently sending demand letters; and (b) coordinate with the HRMO, concerned government agencies, and individuals connected with the AOs, to ascertain the home/business/office address of AOs no longer connected with the LGU, connected with other government agencies, and those with undetermined status, so that demand letters will be effectively served to them;

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to: (i) prepare adjusting journal entries to correct the negative account balance and properly classify the affected accounts; and (ii) conduct detailed collectability assessment and draft a policy on the impairment measurement for the accountabilities of the deceased AOs, for fair presentation of the accounts in the financial statements.

1. Work on the reconciled difference of ₱56,187,136.63 between the accounting and property records, and the result of the actual physical count;
2. Adopt the uniform numbering system for property numbers of PPE and require the Property Unit to update the property stickers based on the prescribed format and to include the required information under Section 5.6 and 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
3. Conduct a physical count of all the PPE, whether acquired through purchase or donation, using the prescribed forms in Annexes of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, and prepare and submit the duly accomplished RPCPPE.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Establish strong internal controls in the handling of cash particularly the collections and remittances made by the Municipal Treasurer to the AGDB, to prevent incurrence of unrecorded collections and/or over-deposit of collections, which may result in an abnormal/negative balance of the Cash-Local Treasury account;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to make an extensive review and evaluation of the accounting records to determine the cause of the abnormal balances and draw a Journal Entry Voucher to correct the deficiency;

Require both the Municipal Accountant-Designate and the Municipal Treasurer, to prepare and maintain under the TF a GL and a Cash Book, respectively, and record all the cash receipts and deposits for funds physically received by the Municipal Treasurer for a specific purpose or undertaking.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant-Designate to:

Conduct regular monitoring and analysis of the CIP account to ensure that all completed projects are transferred to their appropriate PPE accounts;

Reclassify the completed projects costing P16,022,996.37 under the CIP account to their appropriate PPE account; and;

Provide provision for depreciation on completed projects in accordance with the existing rule and regulation.

We recommended, and Management agreed, that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the:

Municipal Treasurer to:

Require all the COs to remit all their collections daily and in case of collectors assigned to the field, at least once a week or as soon as the collections reach ₱5,000.00 to the Municipal Treasurer and prepare the RCD at the close of the business day or on the next working day;

Deposit intact in the full amount of all collections remitted to him;


Avoid issuing new sets of AFs until all collections are remitted in full by the COs;

Record all the transactions of Cash-Local Treasury Accounts to the Cashbook-Cash in Treasury and reflect the correct balance of Cash on hand at a certain date;

Ensure maintenance of all required Cashbooks and strictly monitor that the COs’ Cashbooks are updated and properly accomplished; and


Instruct all the COs to ensure completeness and accuracy of the information on the AFs and RCDs such as signatures and dates.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to intensify their efforts to reconcile their records and effect appropriate adjustments in their respective Cashbook and records, when necessary, to establish the correct balance of the Cash-Local Treasury Account and other affected accounts.

We recommended, and Management agreed, that the LCE require the:

Prepare the necessary correcting entry to adjust the erroneous booking of the PPE accounts, taking into consideration the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000 for recognition as PPE as provided in Section 4 of the Circular;

Prepare and maintain PLCs to ensure completeness of information in the RCPPE and to account for the shortage and overage per item in the PPE;

The Municipal Treasurer as the Property Officer to maintain PC as prescribed under the MNGAS for LGUs.

Moreover, the LCE should mandate the Municipal Accountant-Designate to furnish the auditor with a complete subsidiary schedule of PPE and lapsing schedule for depreciation charges; provide SLs for the CIP account; create an Inventory Committee who are temporarily relieved of all their regular duties, to complete the physical inventory in three (3) months or less and to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the Audit Team, and ensure full implementation of “One Time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular 2020-006; and consider the salvage value of the depreciable assets in computing for the depreciable expense as these, and the above recommendations, are a reiteration of the audit recommendations from the previous audit.

We recommended, and the LCE to direct the HRMO to:

Follow the staffing pattern as the basis for hiring JO and COS workers;

Submit a copy of quantified and detailed Individual Accomplishment Reports to facilitate comparison with the job description stated on their contracts, thereby, ensuring the protection of government funds from unnecessary expenditures.

We recommended, and the Management agreed, that the LCE require:

The Municipal Accountant – Designate to:

Expedite the reconciliation of balances of Inter-Agency Payable accounts and the remittance of monthly premium contributions of the concerned employees to the aforesaid government agencies;

Account fully the prior year’s outstanding balance of the Inter-agency payable accounts;


Analyze the Due to GOCCs account to determine the cause of negative balances;

Reconcile the variance of ₱145,734.98 between the recorded amount in the GL and the ORs;

Make the corresponding adjusting entry to correct the previous entry made in relation to the payment of penalties/interests, to wit:

Dr. Due from Officers and Employees ₱16,962.04
Cr. Government Equity ₱16,962.04

The Municipal Treasurer to remit immediately the reconciled balance of the Inter-Agency Payable account as at December 31, 2021; and

Municipal Accountant-Designate to submit the lacking disbursement vouchers (DVs) and prepare the SLs of the Due to BIR account; and 

Municipal Treasurer to strictly comply with the respective deadlines for the remittance of withheld taxes set forth in BIR Revenue Regulations No. 6-2001 dated July 31, 2001, and BIR Revenue Memorandum Circular No. 23-2007 dated March 20, 2007.

We recommended that the LCE require the members of the GAD Focal Point System (FPS) to:

Conduct gender analysis and administer the use of HGDG tool to determine the cost to be attributed to GAD in the implementation of LGUs major PPAs during GAD PB preparation;

Employ the use of the HGDG test using the PIMME checklist or FIMME checklist to determine actual expenditure that can be attributed to the GAD in the GAD Accomplishment Report (AR);

Submit documentation of projects with no cost incurred as proof that they were actually implemented; and

Strengthen the GAD FPS and immediately establish the GAD database of the LGU.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant-Designate be required to submit the details of the disbursements related to the implementation of GAD PPAs as reported in the GAD AR.

We recommended that Management:
a) Implement controls to timely recognize and process obligations before the
year-end closing;
b) Desist from incurring expenditures not supported with available funds and
approved budget, as such transactions may be disallowed in audit for being
illegal;
c) Direct the Municipal Accountant ensure that expenses are charged to the
appropriate accounting period in compliance with the financial regulations;
d) Ensure proper authorization and utilize appropriate funding mechanisms;
and
e) Provide valid justification, subject to our evaluation and review, explaining
why these transactions should not be disallowed in audit.

We recommended the following measures to the Local Chief Executive to ensure accurate representation and avoid payments more than the delivered accomplishment:
Require the BAC and Engineer/MPDC to conduct inspection within 24 hours upon receipt of the request from the Contractor and accurately reflect the work accomplishment and date of the conduct of inspection in the report;
Require the Engineer to ensure that all inspections are conducted thoroughly with appropriate documentation, including detailed pictures with timestamps, geotagging, and precise description of the work completed;
Implement random cross-checks to verify physical completion and adherence to project specifications; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that payment releases are made only for those sufficiently documented work accomplishments through verified inspections and pictures, and to compute and impose liquidated damages, if necessary.

We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require the:
Municipal Accountant-Designate to:
Refrain from the practice of posting transactions directly to the General Ledger and strictly comply with prescribed accounting procedures, including the preparation of complete and properly documented journal entries prior to postings;
Ensure that all transactions are first recorded in the appropriate books of original entry to establish and maintain a complete and reliable audit trail;
Ensure that all loan-related transactions, including the associated cost such as taxes, fees and charges, are properly accounted in the books;
Apply correct account classification in the recording of loan repayments and embedded costs, in accordance with relevant government accounting standards and chart of accounts;
Conduct thorough review and analysis of all identified errors, including the omitted transactions, and immediately prepare adjusting journal entries to correct the overstatement and understatement of affected accounts;
Municipal Accountant-Designate and Municipal Treasurer to:
Ensure proper coordination by regular and timely provision of source documents related to the loan, such as debit and credit memos, bank statements, and amortization schedules;
Conduct monthly reconciliation of bank records with the General Ledger to identify and address any unrecorded and misposted transactions;
Conduct periodic internal reviews to promptly detect accounting errors, reinforce compliance with IPSAS and other statutory reporting requirements, and strengthen overall financial reporting processes.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct:
The Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator:
Strictly monitor and ensure immediate implementation of all PPAs under the Continuing Appropriation of the 20% Development Fund, with total allocation of ₱21,624,199.00;
Secure all necessary permits and clearances with the DENR-EMB prior to the scheduled implementation of the planned PPAs, to avoid delays and ensure compliance with regulatory requirements;
Ensure that all PPAs included in the AIP are thoroughly planned, technically feasible, and ready for procurement and implementation, in accordance with existing guidelines;
The Municipal Engineer submit the contracts, procurement documents, Statements of Work Accomplished and Inspection Reports of the four (4) PPAs totaling ₱4,657,883.00, which have been declared as implemented as of reporting date, in order to substantiate and verify the reported status of implementation.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to require the:
The Municipal Engineer/Municipal Planning & Development Coordinator/Project Engineer to:
Ensure that any revisions of contract time are properly supported with Suspension of Work Orders or Approved Extension of Contract Time, along with the corresponding resumption orders, to validly justify the revisions made;
Carefully evaluate the conditions cited in the request for extension and grant only those that are justified, ensuring full compliance with the provisions outlined in Annex E of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
Ensure compliance with the contract termination provisions in the event that the contractor incurs more than fifteen percent (15%) negative slippage;
The Municipal Accountant-Designate to:
Compute the liquidated damages for the extensions of contract time which were not supported by Suspension of Work Orders or Approved Extension of Contract Time; and
Ensure that any changes to the terms in the contract, including extensions of contract time, are properly supported by Suspension of Work Orders or Approved Extension of Contract Time before the processing of payments be made to the contractors

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to direct:
The Chairman and Members of the Bids and Awards committee to:
Conduct competitive selection of the Pakyaw Groups, involving of at least three (3) legible groups;
Properly evaluate and document the qualifications and manpower capacity of Pakyaw Groups, ensuring alignment with the manpower requirements specified in the approved Program of Work (POW)
Ensure the execution of Notarized Pakyaw Agreements prior to the implementation of any labor-based projects, to establish a legally binding arrangement and serve as a valid basis for the disbursement of public funds;
Submit the necessary supporting documents for each Pakyaw contract to the Municipal Accountant-Designate;
Ensure that transactions covering the disbursements to Pakyaw Groups are duly supported with complete and appropriate supporting documents before the release of payment.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to:
Establish responsibility center for GFPS under the Officer of the Mayor;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain Subsidiary Ledgers (SL) for each account, assign SL codes and record all GAD related expenses or PPAs;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to provide RC code in the budget; and
Direct the GAD Focal Point System ensure full implementation of GAD PPAs and optimally utilize the allocated GAD Fund by prioritization the implementation of PPAs in the GAD Plan and Budget.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
i) convert the existing MRFs into operational in accordance with Section 32 of R.A. No. 9003;
ii) consider benchmarking with other LGUs with functional MRFs and ask assistance on how to operate the shredding and decomposing machine;
iii) coordinate with EMB on the installation of the shredding and decomposing machines;
iv) require the cooperation of the Barangays in the implementation of Solid Waste Management particularly the establishment of functional MRF and campaign for proper waste segregation; and
v) direct the garbage collectors to wear their protective gears at all times during garbage collection.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Ensure that the implementation, utilization, and disbursement of the LGSF-SBDP are strictly in accordance with the implementing guidelines issued by the DILG;

Instruct the Municipal Engr/MPDC and LGSF-SBDP Focal Person to carefully monitor the implementation of the LGSF-SBDP projects and ensure preparedness of available documents to support the progress billing payments to the contract without undue delay;

Direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to monitor the receipt and utilization of the funds received by the Municipality and ensure that disbursement are made within the validity of the fund; and

Require the Municipal Treasurer to immediately refund the unutilized balance of the FY 2022 LGSF-SBDP fund to the DILG amounting to P380,956.92 and the corresponding FUR.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the 

(a) City Engineer to be attentive to the reasons given by the contractor on their request for extension; 

(b) City Development Council Executive Committee to strengthen the planning of the PPAs to ensure their timely implementation;

 (c) Bids and Awards Committee, BAC Secretariat, and Technical Working Group to (i) submit copies of Performance Security of the winning bidders for the 12 infrastructure projects; otherwise, provide satisfactory explanation of the non-submission thereof; and 

(ii) strictly comply with pertinent provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its IRR in all procurements; and 

(c) City Accountant to strengthen her review function on the requisite documentation of procurements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Require the Human Resource and Management officer to assess its existing Organizational Structure so that the ideal number of plantilla personnel will be established and submit a report with recommendations thereon to the LCE for approval by the appropriate bodies;

Require the HRMO to create policies and guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring JOs taking into consideration the existing regular employees;

Require the HRMO to limit the hiring of personnel under Job Order contracts to those extremely necessary and deploy only to offices that are actually in need of their services;

Require Job Orders to submit primary personal identification, undergo interview and evaluate the performance of each to give assurance that the risk identified above are addressed; and,

Require the HRMO to incorporate in the contract the necessary details such as the job description/specific work to be done, the certification as to the necessity of hiring the Job Order, certification as to the existence of the appropriation, and that the person duly signified the intent which was considered by the hiring agency.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require the 

(a) GSO to (i) find ways on how to facilitate the uploading of data in the PIAS; 

(ii) ensure that the demand letter issued to the accountable officers are in official form; 

(iii) prepare IIRUP for the identified unserviceable, obsolete or idle items that are no longer needed in operation and recommend for their disposal in accordance with the prescribed guidelines; 

(iv) update or establish accountability on PPEs through the issuance or renewal of PARs; 

(b) Accounting Unit and the GSO to (i) reconcile the differences in their records as to the valuation and re-classification of PPE items; and 

(ii) ensure that the procedures required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 on the one-time PPE cleansing are completed within the ensuing year.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the 

(a) Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories and submit the Report on Physical Count of Inventories to the Audit Team; 

(b) City General Services Officer to regularly prepare and submit the RIS and SSMI to the CAO; and 

(c) CAO to (i) consistently adopt the perpetual inventory method in accounting for said asset; 

(ii) prepare and maintain SLCs; 

(iii) ensure the correct classification of inventories and its corresponding expense accounts; and 

(iv) draw adjusting entries to correct the following errors noted in audit

11. We recommended that the LDRRMO coordinate with the OCD on the preparation and submission of the Municipality’s PSCP pursuant to NDRRMC Memorandum No. 33, s. 2018.
12. We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
a) To conduct risk assessment;
b) To identify critical processes and functions;
c) To determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
d) To conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
e) To formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed templates and requirements in the PSCP guidebook; and
f) To submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the Local Chief Executive for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Assessor to update the Assessment Roll to establish a realistic and accurate RPT and SET receivables and to regularly submit them to the MTO; 

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to update her records as to RPT/SET Receivable Accounts basing on the updated Assessment Roll from the Municipal Assessor and forward such before the set-up of receivables at the beginning of the year;

through the Municipal Accountant, reconcile records with the Municipal Treasurer and thereafter, effect the corresponding adjusting entries to provide correct balances in the ensuing Financial Statements; and

intensify revenue collection efforts by strictly enforcing existing tax laws and adopt the most efficient, effective and economic measures to improve the LGU’s collection system and revenue generation.

Exhaust all means to retrieve records or documents to support/establish the claim of the municipal government against the accountable persons with long outstanding cash advances;
If not possible, avail of the remedies set forth by COA on the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of accounts as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Direct the concerned accountable officers and employees, in writing through a demand letter and copy furnish the audit team, to liquidate or settle immediately all outstanding cash advances; and
Undertake measures to strengthen internal control on the grant and liquidation of cash advances by adhering to pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997.

Require the Municipal Accountant to constantly (i) review and monitor the lapsing schedule of the PPE and ensure the accuracy of data like the date of acquisition, cost, and estimated useful life for the computation of depreciation expense; and (ii) ensure that all PPEs subject for depreciation are provided with correct depreciation expense;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to properly accomplish the RPCI, RPCPPE, and IIRUP and submit them to audit team on time; and
Enjoin the original parties in the lost Deed of Sale to execute a new one, provided that earnest effort was already exerted and documented to locate the previous Deed, so that the management could commence already the processing of transfer of ownership to the local government.

We recommended that Management:
strictly adhere to Section 2.6 of LBC No. 124 on the budget and utilization of COVID-19-related expenses and to the abovementioned budgeting laws, rules and regulations;
prepare a well-planned LDRRM Fund PPAs to avoid uncoordinated processing of transactions that results to improper budgeting, utilization of funds and implementation of projects;
ensure that before recording supplies and materials to expense accounts, issuance thereof is properly documented and submitted to the accounting office for proper accounting and recording;
submit the lacking liquidation reports and/or distribution lists of the procurement and issuance to beneficiaries of medical oxygen cylinders and regulators, antigen test kits and medicines; and
ensure that the modular tents and monoblock chairs as well as other equipment/supplies and materials acquired with cost less than ₱15,000.00 are properly issued with ICS and submit copies to COA for validation.

We recommended that Management:
require the concerned accountable officers to settle/liquidate their outstanding cash advances and/or refund unused portion, otherwise, enforce applicable sanctions;
stop the grant of additional cash advances to personnel with unliquidated cash advances;
establish controls to ensure full and timely liquidation of cash advances, such as (1) securing enough copies that may include the accountable official/employees’ copy; (2) requiring complete documentary requirements not only upon liquidation, but even upon the granting thereof to establish accountability; and (3) directing the Municipal Treasurer to rather request the check payees to come to the LGU in order to safekeep the disbursement vouchers intact inside the LGU;
formally demand from the two concerned Accountable Officers to submit the copy of the duly received transmittal letter of the direct liquidation of intelligence/confidential funds totaling ₱793,500.00, and confirm in writing to COA ICFAU the status of this transactions; and
continue retrieval of pertinent documents to establish the accountability of ₱397,650.74 inherited balances under Advances to Officers and Employees account, then formally demand liquidation or refund once accountability is identified.

We recommended that Management:
direct the GFPS to fully implement GPB and monitor implementation thereof to ensure that no PPAs are left unimplemented at year-end;
prepare GAD Accomplishment Report based on the GPB previously reviewed and endorsed by DILG, fill out columns therein with appropriate and adequate information, and attach relevant supporting documents;
implement a defined monitoring and evaluation system to properly assess the status and impact of GAD PPAs on gender mainstreaming; and
endorse the designated GFPS to GAD related training for their necessary knowledge and skills in heading GAD budgeting, implementation and reporting.

We recommended that Management strictly comply with the following: 
Submit the lacking documentary requirements;
Submit written explanations and/or justifications on why the violations were committed;
Avoid procuring goods that were not included in the APP and in the supplemental procurement plans; and
Ensure that future procurement of land should be in accordance with the IRR of RA 10752 and with Section 13.1 of COA Circular 2012-001.

We recommended and management agreed that the Municipal Mayor require the:

Inventory Committee to (i) conduct the complete physical count of all inventories and property, plant and equipment (PPE) in accordance with Section 124 of Volume I of Manual on NGAS for LGUs; (ii) properly prepare/accomplish the corresponding RPCI and RPCPPE; and (iii) submit the reports to the Audit Team within the timeframe provided by the same regulation;





Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustments in the books to correct all the erroneous recording/classification noted and henceforth, ensure proper recording/classification of the properties in accordance with the Chart of Accounts provided in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015; 

Concerned accountable officer to explain for the “cannot be located or lost” properties and render an account for those properties pursuant to Section 494 of the GAAM;

 Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to (i) exert efforts in identifying and providing the details of all the PPE accounts on the RPCPPE; and (ii) always reconcile the result of the count with the property records and accounting records; and



Municipal Treasurer to make a report of unserviceable/non-functional PPEs in the IIRUP which could be undertaken simultaneously with the physical inventory for disposal and eventual proper relief of accountabilities.

We recommended the following:

the Municipal Mayor require the BAC to ensure proper compliance with the requirements prescribed under the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to prevent the same lapses in future procurements.  Also, submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated.  Moreover, furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract of Agreement and its attachments within five (5) working days from the execution thereof as required under Item 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009;

the Municipal Mayor always take appropriate action regarding the non-completion of projects within the target completion date as provided in Annex E of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;

the Municipal Engineer (i) ensure that all the necessary reports/documents are properly prepared; and (ii) observe strict compliance with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, specifically Annex E and COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 dated February 27, 2005 in the grant of time extension; and

the Municipal Accountant (i) see to it that supporting documents attached to the vouchers are valid, proper and legal and supported with complete documentation before processing the claims in accordance with Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 and Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160; (ii) submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001; and (iii) be guided by Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 in recording the transactions of the Municipality.

We recommended and the LCE is amenable to direct the 

(a) Chairman, Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to ensure that (i) the necessary procurement information are timely posted in GPPB portal and PhilGEPS; 

(ii) POs and OSS include warranty clause in accordance with Guidelines for Emergency Procurement under Bayanihan to Heal as One Act; and 

(b) City Accountant to (i) recognize in the books the procured equipment and inventory consistent with Section 51 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I; 

(ii) submit the above lacking documents and information to the Audit Team; and 


(iii) ensure that future disbursements are adequately documented.

We recommended and the LCE concurred to instruct the City Accountant to 

(a) observe the proper accounting of BGCM transactions through the use of SAGF; 

(b) use the prescribed accounts for inventories; 

(c) provide the above lacking documents and information; and 

(d) ensure that future disbursements are adequately documented.

We recommended and the Management agreed to 

(a) secure an SP ordinance to legalize the imposition and collection of fees by POWAS; 

(b) establish an internal control system for POWAS operation with the end view of securing collections from loss or misuse and ensuring that government funds are legally and properly utilized.

We recommended that:

A list of all on-going government projects/programs/activities and those that are to be implemented during the year be submitted to the Office of the Auditor at the beginning of the year. The list shall include the following information as prescribed under COA Circular 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013:

project name; 
brief description of the PPA; 
contractor or supplier, if any; 
mode of procurement; 
funding source; 
cost or approved budget; 
project duration including start and completion dates; and
location.

The Office of the Municipal Mayor, in coordination with the Office of the Municipal Engineer for infrastructure projects or with the concerned Department Heads for non-infrastructure projects/program/activities, timely inform the Auditor through a letter that the appropriate signboard is already posted after award of an infrastructure project or before the start of a program/activity.

We recommended the following:

The LDRRMO (i) prepare and submit the LDRRMFIP and Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRM to the Audit Team in accordance with Items 5.1.2 and 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; (ii) consider the requisitions of items needed to maintain pre-positioned food packs and hygiene kits for at least 500 families at any given time in compliance with the minimum standards and pursuant to NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1; and (iii) attend trainings on the conduct of Rapid Damage Assessment Needs Analysis (RDANA);

The Municipal Mayor consider the provision of additional manpower at the LDRRM Office pursuant to Section 5.2 of the JMC No. 2014-1 dated April 4, 2014 bearing in mind the provision of Section 325(a) of R.A. No. 7160;

The Property and Supply Officer always ensure that issuances of small tangible items with serviceable life of more than one year and property, plant and equipment are supported with Inventor Custodian Slip (ICS) and Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE), respectively, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2005-002 and Section 42 of the MNGAS, Volume II for LGUs;

The Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the guidelines set forth by (i) COA Circular No. 2012-002 and COA Circular No. 2014-002 for proper accounting and recording of the utilization of the LDRRM Fund; (ii) Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 for proper documentation of transactions; and (iii) COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 for proper recording of transactions of the Municipality; and 

The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly adhere to the requirements of Annex H of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 on the procurement of goods and services thru Small Value Procurement.

We recommended the following:

the Municipal Mayor require the BAC to ensure proper compliance with the requirements prescribed under the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to prevent the same lapses in future procurements.  Meanwhile, cause the investigation on the procurement procedures adopted by the BAC on the subject 13 projects and hold accountable those found remiss of their respective duties and functions.  Also, submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated.  Moreover, furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract of Agreement and its attachments within five (5) working days from the execution thereof as required under Section 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009;

the Municipal Mayor always take appropriate action regarding the non-completion of projects within the target completion date;

the Municipal Engineer (i) ensure that all the necessary reports/documents are properly prepared; and (ii) observe strict compliance with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, specifically Annex E and COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 dated February 27, 2005 in the grant of time extension; and

the Municipal Accountant (i) see to it that supporting documents attached to the vouchers are valid, proper and legal and supported with complete documentation before processing the claims in accordance with Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 and Section 474 b(5) of R.A. No. 7160; (ii) submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and COA Circular No. 2012-001; and (iii) be guided by Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 in recording the transactions of the Municipality.

We recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor and LGU GFPS Technical Working Group (TWG) comply with the comments and recommendations made by the DILG Provincial Office on their GPB so as not to put the efforts of the Reviewing Officer in vain.  But in any event that they could not proceed with the originally prepared GPB, they should always adhere to the provision of Section 6.0.C.7.2 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01;

The LGU GFPS TWG (i) conduct a gender analysis of their attributed programs and projects through the administration of the HGDG tool as prescribed under Section 3.0.C.4.1.a of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01; (ii) ensure compliance with Section 7.0 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 on the preparation and submission of the GAD Accomplishment Report (AR); (iii) ensure that the result of HGDG Assessment is accurate; (iv) prepare the Annual GAD AR in coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to avoid discrepancies in the reports prepared; and (v) submit to the Audit Team the GAD AR in accordance with Item V of COA Circular No. 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014;

The Municipal Accountant be guided by Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 for proper documentation of transactions; and

