Based on the foregoing audit observations, we reiterated our previous recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:

a.	require all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate their outstanding cash advances giving more emphasis to the long outstanding cash advances;

b.  resort to the withholding of salaries of those accountable officers and employees who still fail or persistently refuse to settle/liquidate their cash advances;

c. exert extra efforts to recover outstanding cash advances from Accountable Officers who are no longer in the service nor connected with the municipality;

d.	require strictly an Office Clearance from Money and Property accountabilities, pursuant to Sections 200 and 256, Vol. I of the Government Accounting and Auditing Manual from all personnel who seek retirement, resignation, transfer or claim for death benefits in order that all accountabilities could be appropriately settled;

e.	directs the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting additional cash advances to any official or employee unless previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, pursuant to Section 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and

f.  require the Municipal Accountant to maintain Subsidiary Ledgers and schedules for the accounts used for cash advances to facilitate monitoring of the amount outstanding per employee, to ensure that no additional cash advance will be granted to those with outstanding balances and to support the amounts reflected in the financial statements and submit same to the Audit Team.

Based on the foregoing observations, we recommended that:

a.  the Municipal Mayor along with all the concerned officials and employees identify the priority needs of its constituents and strictly follow, among others, Item 5.0 of Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 of the DILG and DBM in the implementation of programs/projects/activities for the 20% Development Fund;

the Municipal Engineer coordinate, monitor and evaluate the implementation of those projects to avoid delays and maximize the utilization of the 20% Local Development Fund in accordance with DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1;

the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to identify the individual PAPs in the AIP and refrain from inputting lump sum/generic term appropriation; and

with regard to its cash deficit, the management should: a) conduct regular budget review to determine the financial viability of the municipality at a certain time of year; b) carry out periodic performance analyses to be able to determine how to improve its collection efficiency and adopt strategies to intensify collections that would improve its financial viability; and c) strictly observe the austerity measures in the government under AO No. 103 dated August 31, 2004 and reduce/trim down expenditures so as not to hamper the services and priority projects intended for the constituents.

